Complex Function: The nuclear mitotic cohesin complex is primarily responsible for sister chromatid cohesion during cell division. Complex Name: Ndc80 Complex (also known as HEC1 complex in humans)
Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster
Complex Function: The Ndc80 complex is a crucial component of the kinetochore;  serving as the primary microtubule-binding interface during mitosis. It establishes and maintains the connection between kinetochores and spindle microtubules;  facilitating chromosome alignment and segregation during mitosis. The complex also plays a key role in spindle assembly checkpoint signaling;  ensuring proper chromosome segregation by delaying anaphase onset until all chromosomes are properly attached to the spindle.
Proteins: Ndc80 (also known as HEC1 in humans); Nuf2; Spc24; Spc25

Other Organisms: Human;  Mouse;  C. elegans;  Drosophila melanogaster

It functions to establish and maintain the end-on attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochores during mitosis and meiosis;  which is essential for proper chromosome segregation. The complex also plays a role in the spindle assembly checkpoint (SAC) signaling;  which prevents anaphase onset until all chromosomes are properly attached to the spindle.
Proteins: Ndc80 (also called Hec1 or TID3);  Nuf2;  Spc24;  Spc25

It forms a dumbbell-shaped heterotetramer that bridges between the inner kinetochore and the microtubules. This complex is essential for establishing and maintaining proper kinetochore-microtubule attachments during mitosis;  ensuring accurate chromosome segregation. It also participates in the spindle assembly checkpoint signaling;  which prevents anaphase onset until all chromosomes are properly attached to the mitotic spindle.
Proteins: Ndc80 (also known as Hec1 in humans);  Nuf2;  Spc24;  Spc25

The complex specifically provides a structural platform that bridges the chromatin-proximal components with the microtubule-binding modules of the KMN (KNL1;  Mis12;  Ndc80) network.

The complex is essential for proper kinetochore assembly;  ensuring accurate chromosome alignment and segregation during cell division.

Complex Function: The CCM complex functions as a critical regulator of vascular integrity and endothelial cell junctions in the central nervous system. It maintains the integrity of blood vessels by regulating RhoA-ROCK signaling;  controlling endothelial cell-cell junctions;  and promoting vascular quiescence. When dysfunctional;  it leads to cerebral cavernous malformations - dilated;  thin-walled vascular lesions primarily in the brain that can cause hemorrhage;  seizures;  and neurological deficits.

It helps to coordinate helicase activity with DNA polymerase action and stabilizes interactions between multiple replication factors.

Complex Function: The CMG helicase complex functions as the primary replicative helicase during DNA replication in eukaryotes. It is activated during the transition from G1 to S phase when the pre-replicative complex (pre-RC) is converted to an active replication fork.
